GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 958
Short Title: Election Law Changes. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Blackwell and Stevens (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Election Law, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO ELECTION ADMINISTRATION LAWS
3 AND CAMPAIGN FINANCE LAWS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 163-22 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
6 "(u) In educating voters, the State Board shall not use its role to recruit or encourage voters
7 to associate with any political party over another or to influence voter turnout for a particular
8 political party."
9 SECTION 2. G.S. 163-90.2(a) reads as rewritten:
10 "(a) When any challenge is sustained for any cause listed under G.S. 163-85(c), the board
11 shall cancel or correct the voter registration of the voter. The county board shall maintain such
12 record for at least six months and during the pendency of any appeal. The Except for challenges
13 sustained for cause listed under G.S. 163-85(c)(6), the challenged ballot shall be counted for any
14 ballot items for which the challenged voter is eligible to vote, as if it were a provisional official
15 ballot under the provisions of G.S. 163-166.11(4). For any challenge sustained for death of the
16 voter under G.S. 163-85(c)(6), the challenged ballot shall not be counted if the voter died between
17 the time the ballot was cast and 6:30 A.M. on election day."
18 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 163-165.5(a)(4) reads as rewritten:
19 "(4) Party designations in partisan ballot items. Party designations shall be printed
20 in the same font type and size as the name of the candidate."
21 SECTION 3.(b) This section becomes effective January 1, 2026, and applies to
22 elections held on or after that date.
23 SECTION 4. G.S. 163-166.35(a) reads as rewritten:
24 "(a) A county board of elections by unanimous vote of all its members may provide for
25 one or more sites in that county for ballots to be applied for and cast under this Part. Each county
26 board shall open at least one early voting site for every 30,000 registered voters, or any portion
27 thereof, registered in that county as of July 1 of the previous calendar year. The county board
28 shall seek to provide geographic diversity when selecting locations for early voting sites. Except
29 for individuals appointed to early voting sites pursuant to subsection (b) of this section, every
30 individual staffing any of those sites shall be a member or full-time employee of the county board
31 of elections or an employee of the county board of elections whom the board has given training
32 equivalent to that given a full-time employee. Those sites must be approved by the State Board
33 as part of a Plan for Implementation approved by both the county board of elections and by the
34 State Board which shall also provide adequate security of the ballots and provisions to avoid
35 allowing persons to vote who have already voted. A county board of elections may propose in its
*H958-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Plan for Implementation not to offer early voting at the county board of elections office; the State
2 Board may approve that proposal in a Plan for Implementation only if the Plan for
3 Implementation includes at least one site reasonably proximate to the county board of elections
4 office and the State Board finds that the sites in the Plan for Implementation as a whole provide
5 adequate coverage of the county's electorate. If a county board of elections has considered a
6 proposed Plan or Plans for Implementation and has been unable to reach unanimity in favor of a
7 Plan for Implementation, a member or members of that county board of elections may petition
8 the State Board to adopt a plan for it. If petitioned, the State Board may also receive and consider
9 alternative petitions from another member or members of that county board. The State Board
10 may adopt a Plan for Implementation for that county. The State Board, in that plan, shall take
11 into consideration whether the Plan for Implementation disproportionately favors any party,
12 racial or ethnic group, or candidate."
13 SECTION 5. G.S. 163-182.1(b)(1) reads as rewritten:
14 "(1) Provide for a sample hand-to-eye count of the paper ballots of a statewide
15 ballot item in every county. The presidential ballot item shall be the subject of
16 the sampling in a presidential election. If there is no statewide ballot item, the
17 State Board Auditor shall provide a process for selecting district or local ballot
18 items to adequately sample the electorate. The State Board shall approve in an
19 open meeting the procedure for randomly selecting the sample precincts for
20 each election. The random selection of precincts for any county shall be done
21 publicly after the initial count of election returns for that county is publicly
22 released or 24 hours after the polls close on election day, whichever is earlier.
23 The sample chosen by the State Board Auditor shall be of one or more full
24 precincts, full counts of mailed absentee ballots, full counts of one or more
25 early voting sites, or a combination. The size of the sample of each category
26 shall be chosen to produce a statistically significant result and shall be chosen
27 after consultation with a statistician. The actual units shall be chosen at
28 random. In the event of a material discrepancy between the electronic or
29 mechanical count and a hand-to-eye count, the hand-to-eye count shall
30 control, except where paper ballots have been lost or destroyed or where there
31 is another reasonable basis to conclude that the hand-to-eye count is not the
32 true count. If the discrepancy between the hand-to-eye count and the
33 mechanical or electronic count is significant, a complete hand-to-eye count
34 shall be conducted."
35 SECTION 6.(a) G.S. 163-182.2(a), as amended by Section 3A.4(e) of S.L. 2024-57,
36 reads as rewritten:
37 "(a) The initial counting of official ballots cast on election day and under Part 5 of Article
38 14A of this Chapter shall be conducted according to the following principles:
39 …
40 (4) If the county board finds that an individual voting a provisional official ballot
41 (i) was registered in the county as provided in 163-82.1, (ii) voted in the proper
42 precinct under G.S. 163-55 and G.S. 163-57, and (iii) was otherwise eligible
43 to vote, the provisional official ballots shall be counted by the county board
44 no later than 5:00 P.M. on the third business day after the election. election;
45 provided, however, for counties with over 250,000 registered voters in that
46 election, the provisional official ballots shall be counted by the county board
47 no later than 5:00 P.M. on the fifth business day after the election. Except as
48 provided in G.S. 163-82.15(e), if the county board finds that an individual
49 voting a provisional official ballot (i) did not vote in the proper precinct under
50 G.S. 163-55 and G.S. 163-57, (ii) is not registered in the county as provided
51 in G.S. 163-82.1, or (iii) is otherwise not eligible to vote, the ballot shall not
