12 c. Include the number of provisional ballots cast in that precinct and the
13 number of outstanding provisional ballots cast in that precinct.
14 …."
15 SECTION 6.(b) G.S. 163-234, as amended by Section 3A.4(g) of S.L. 2024-57,
16 reads as rewritten:
17 "§ 163-234. Counting absentee ballots by county board.
18 All absentee ballots returned to the county board in the container-return envelopes shall be
19 retained by the county board to be counted by the county board as follows:
20 …
21 (2) The county board shall meet at 5:00 P.M. on election day in the county board
22 office or other public location in the county courthouse for the purpose of
23 counting all absentee ballots except those which have been challenged before
24 5:00 P.M. on election day day, those described in subdivision (13) of this
25 section, and those received pursuant to G.S. 163-231(b)(2). Any elector of the
26 county shall be permitted to attend the meeting and allowed to observe the
27 counting process, so long as the elector does not in any manner interfere with
28 the election officials in the discharge of their duties. The count of these
29 absentee ballots shall be continuous until completed, and the members shall
30 not separate or leave the counting place except for unavoidable necessity.
31 The county board may begin counting absentee ballots issued under
32 Article 21A of this Chapter between the hours of 9:00 A.M. and 5:00 P.M.
33 and may begin counting all absentee ballots between the hours of 2:00 P.M.
34 and 5:00 P.M. upon the adoption of a resolution at least two weeks prior to the
35 election in which the hour and place of counting absentee ballots shall be
36 stated. A copy of the resolution shall be published once a week for two weeks
37 prior to the election, in a newspaper having general circulation in the county.
38 Notice may additionally be made on a radio or television station or both, but
39 the notice shall be in addition to the newspaper and other required notice. The
40 count shall be continuous until completed and the members shall not separate
41 or leave the counting place except for unavoidable necessity, except that if the
42 count has been completed prior to the time the polls close, it shall be
43 suspended until that time pending receipt of any additional ballots. Nothing in
44 this section prohibits a county board from taking preparatory steps for the
45 count earlier than the times specified in this section, as long as the preparatory
46 steps do not reveal to any individual not engaged in the actual count election
47 results before the times specified in this subdivision for the count to begin. By
48 way of illustration and not limitation, a preparatory step for the count would
49 be the entry of tally cards from direct record electronic voting units into a
50 computer for processing. The county board shall not announce the result of
51 the count before 7:30 P.M.
